  pages = {229--243},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Argues that if we can prevent something bad from happening
  without sacrificing anything of comparable moral importance, we ought morally
  to do it. Applied to world poverty, this generates stringent obligations for
  affluent individuals to donate substantial portions of their income to famine
  relief and poverty reduction. The argument relies on a utilitarian principle
  combined with the empirical claim that donations can effectively prevent
  suffering. Singer contends that distance and proximity are morally irrelevant—
  our duty to save a drowning child nearby is the same as our duty to save
  distant strangers through charitable giving.

  RELEVANCE: This is the foundational text for utilitarian arguments about
  charitable giving. The research project investigates income vs. asset-based
  giving norms, and Singer's argument implicitly focuses on disposable income as
  the resource from which giving obligations derive. Understanding how Singer
  defines "comparable moral importance" and what resources are considered
  "sacrificable" is essential for evaluating whether income and assets should be
  treated differently in utilitarian frameworks.

  POSITION: Strong utilitarian consequentialism with agent-neutral impartial
  beneficence; foundational text establishing the problem space.
  },
